<TEXT>
prime minister margaret thatcher appointed new 
foreign and defense secretaries monday fired two cabinet ministers 
and switched around others in the biggest government shakeup since 
she won power 10 years ago 
mrs thatcher named john major one of the leastknown members 
of her 22member cabinet as the new foreign secretary making him 
a prime contender to succeed her 
he replaces sir geoffrey howe who was moved to a vacant post as 
deputy prime minister howe will also lead the governing 
conservative party in the house of commons 
the prime minister battling to halt her governments slide in 
popularity also put new appointees in an array of major posts 
including the portfolios for northern ireland and the environment 
mrs thatcher fired her harassed transport secretary paul 
channon who had been accused of bungling bomb warnings before pan 
am flight 103 was blown up over scotland on dec 21 and social 
security secretary john moore 
the two other cabinet ministers to depart defense secretary 
george younger and trade and industry secretary lord young said 
they were resigning to resume business careers 
northern ireland secretary tom king was named defense secretary 
in an apparent reward after four years as britains top official in 
the embattled province 
the appointment of major as foreign secretary was a big step up 
from his former cabinet post as chief secretary to the treasury 
the no 2 financial official 
the 46yearold son of a circus trapeze artist was raised in 
poverty in south londons rundown brixton district never went to 
university and worked as a building laborer before making a career 
in banking 
he entered parliament in the may 1979 general election that 
brought mrs thatcher to power and ousted a socialist labor party 
government 
his appointment underlined the transformation of the hierarchy 
of the conservative party once the preserve of the british upper 
classes since mrs thatcher a grocers daughter took over 
we now know without the need for guesswork who her chosen 
successor will be londons liberal guardian newspaper commented 
tuesday 
mrs thatcher 63 is widely expected to retire some time after 
bidding for an unprecedented fourth successive term at the next 
election it must be held by mid1992 
the move of howe 62 to deputy prime minister was widely 
regarded as a demotion from one of the most prestigious jobs in the 
cabinet 
mrs thatcher also brought into the cabinet another member of 
the class of 1979 christopher patten a rising star from the 
partys liberal wing as the new environment secretary 
reflecting anxiety at the governments drop in the polls and its 
drubbing in elections for the european parliament last month mrs 
thatcher shifted education secretary kenneth baker to the 
chairmanship of the conservative party 
party chairman peter brooke was named northern ireland 
secretary a tough job that effectively removes the incumbent from 
daytoday contact with party political issues in mainland britain 
energy secretary cecil parkinson a thatcher favorite whose 
political career was interrupted after a scandal over an 
extramarital liaison six years ago was named transport secretary 
he resigned from the cabinet in 1983 after news broke that his 
exsecretary with whom he had an affair was carrying his child 
mrs thatcher brought him back into the cabinet when she won a 
third term in may 1987 
the shakeup announced after mrs thatcher summoned government 
ministers to her downing street office for private meetings 
appeared aimed primarily at freshening the governments image 
beset by rising inflation a revival of labor union militancy 
and facing a much tougher challenge from the revived labor party 
mrs thatcher has trailed labor seven to 15 points in polls since 
the spring 
patten succeeded nicholas ridley a chainsmoking scion of an 
aristocratic family who was named trade and industry secretary 
ridley accused by critics of mishandling the current passage 
through parliament of a controversial new tax is deeply unpopular 
with many party members who blame him for worsening the 
governments poll standing 
but mrs thatcher who has the sole power to appoint cabinet 
ministers has repeatedly defended him 
the dismissal of transport secretary channon an heir to the 
guinness brewing fortune and reputedly the richest member of the 
cabinet had been predicted 
in the aftermath of the pan am disaster his department was 
accused of being tardy about passing on detailed bomb warnings to 
airlines critics also said he mishandled current strikes by 
employees of british rail and the london underground 
other new cabinet appointments announced were norman lamont as 
treasury secretary and john gummer as agriculture minister both 
previously held government jobs outside the cabinet 
john wakeham conservative party leader in the commons became 
the new energy secretary and tony newton former trade minister 
the new social security secretary 
</TEXT>
