<TEXT>
george bush rebounding from negative reviews 
early in his presidency is now winning good marks after two 
successful trips to europe and a general sense of economic 
wellbeing at home 
the president is a late bloomer says one analyst 
at the 100day point bush was criticized as being too cautious 
unimaginative and unwilling to compete with soviet leader mikhail 
s gorbachev 
after six months in office bush basks in praise for winning 
support at a nato summit for a us plan to reduce conventional 
arms in europe and for traveling to poland and hungary to 
encourage democratic reforms 
hes actually done well after a halting beginning said 
thomas cronin a presidential scholar at colorado college 
cronin said bush was aided enormously by the fact that the 
democrats in congress were in disarray as house speaker jim 
wright of texas and house whip tony coelho of california struggled 
with ethical problems and then resigned there was no challenge 
to his leadership 
after losing a battle with congress for confirmation of john 
tower as secretary of defense bush came back with a decisive 
victory on his veto of a 120 increase in the minimum wage 
hes obviously in a lot better shape than he was at 100 
days said stephen hess a presidential scholar at the brookings 
institution hes had two awfully good trips abroad and when a 
president travels abroad he gets an awful lot of attention 
larry sabato the university of virginia political scientist who 
called bush a late bloomer said its as though theres a second 
honeymoon at the sixmonth point 
its tied to real successes particularly in the foreign 
sphere and things are going reasonably well abroad and at home 
sabato said the economy may be slow but its not in recession 
theres no war or threat of it and things appear to be going in 
our direction 
norman ornstein a political analyst at the american enterprise 
institute said bushs foreign travels tilt the balance away from 
the notion that the guy who was making things happen was gorbachev 
and that bush was asleep at the switch 
it erases the notion of a passive president whos doing 
nothing ornstein said 
at the white house bushs chief of staff john sununu said 
its nice to see the beginning of a response that everybody hoped 
there would be 
polls show bush has a positive rating of 66 to 73 percent which 
puts him ahead of ronald reagan at this point in his presidency 
andy kohut president of gallup opinion research said bushs 
approval rating was slipping in april and may but then began to 
turn around 
between may and july hes been dealing with international 
problems and the country tends to rally around a president whos 
dealing with rather clearcut international issues said kohut 
on the other hand kohut said bush is still an enigmatic 
character to many people thats where hes weak he said the 
category of people classified as dont know or no opinion 
about bush is higher than with other presidents running at about 
26 percent 
countering that criticism sununu said vision doesnt fit on a 
bumper sticker 
he said the president is defining his agenda with specific 
proposals to balance the budget bail out the savings and loan 
industry clean up air pollution and combat crime 
sununu said bush has demonstrated a willingness to do his 
homework to spend the time examining the details then to make a 
decision not in haste 
asked what bush should have done differently sununu replied 
honest in terms of the big issues and timetable and the agenda 
and the approach not a heck of a lot 
ornstein said bush should be more aggressive establish a 
longterm agenda and take some risks beyond that he said bush was 
losing an awful lot of direction and momentum by the fact that 
hundreds of toplevel appointments have not been made 
he could plummet the next six months if we slipped into a 
recession cautioned sabato 
theres a little too much basking in the glow of a 70 percent 
approval rating not capitalizing on it ornstein said if 
youre up around 70 percent early on its a good time to let it 
drop down to 60 percent by pushing some things through that may be 
a little controversial 
there is widespread agreement that much of bushs popularity is 
due to his personal style his high energy level and obvious relish 
for the job 
i think weve grown used to him like an old comfortable 
shoe said hess some of the rough edges from the campaign have 
rubbed off he hasnt forced himself on us 
ornstein said bush is not the kind of guy whos going to fall 
asleep with the pope alluding to an occasion where reagan 
nodded off while meeting with john paul ii 
sununu said i think people right off the bat perceived a 
different style from the reagan days they have really begun to 
feel comfortable and appreciative of the style i think that is 
very important for a president to do to give his mark to the 
office that he probably will be occupying for eight years 
