<TEXT>
the revolt of japanese voters against the liberal 
democratic party gave a strong boost to the socialists but 
analysts say it was far more conservative than the result would 
indicate 
in sundays election the conservative liberal democrats lost 
their majority in the upper house of parliament for the first time 
since the party was formed 34 years ago 
the socialists gained 24 seats thanks to support from women 
farmers and others disgruntled with the governing partys scandals 
and economic policies 
a record number of women candidates 22 won their races 
socialist party chairman takako doi attracted adoring crowds of 
women who wore pink scarves and applauded her criticism of the 
liberal democrats 
when sousuke uno announced his resignation monday women reveled 
in their role in helping remove him their anger over allegations 
that he had kept paid mistresses hampered unos efforts to restore 
his partys reputation after an influencebuying scandal forced 
predecessor noboru takeshita to quit less than two months ago 
breadandbutter issues appeared to be even more important 
i really believe that this was a peoples revolution coming 
from the kitchen said kazuo shinsaka of the laborbacked rengo 
no kai a new party who won election in nara 
the socialists dont propose nationalizing industries or 
equalizing incomes but talk of restoring faith in politics 
repealing the new 3 percent sales tax reestablishing protection 
for farmers who complain about more open import policies and 
improving the environment 
many women candidates campaigned not as feminists but as 
ordinary housewives defending their homes against the sales tax 
what this vote shows is that people want a return to the 
status quo said seisaburo sato a political analyst it was 
the ldp that tried to change things 
kuniko inoguchi and other analysts said the economic prosperity 
that has characterized more than three decades of liberal 
democratic government may have encouraged the discontent 
when the economy is good people can afford to be critical 
inoguchi said they can afford to worry about issues of justice 
the ldp had modern policies but closed premodern political 
practices they were telling everybody to adjust to change 
economic liberalization and internationalization but didnt make 
an effort to change themselves 
although the liberal democrats still may have a protectionist 
reputation abroad they have made major changes in the past few 
years usually under foreign pressure 
beginning four years ago the government helped the yen rise and 
import barriers fall enough to transform the structure of the 
economy and hurt important groups such as the farmers 
economic growth still robust now comes more from domestic 
consumption and investment than exports 
japanese are richer than ever before and mamanufactured imports 
have increased 78 percent since 1985 protection of agriculture is 
being chipped away 
a tax reform package many experts consider economically sound 
but clumsily introduced has given salaried workers more money to 
spend and may help bring japans economy more in line with those of 
its trading partners the sales tax part has outraged housewives 
however 
women seek change in several areas they have joined the labor 
force in record numbers helped by an equal opportunity law but 
often in poorly paid parttime jobs 
affluence has meant free time and more education but women are 
angered by lingering discrimination exemplified by agriculture 
minister hisao horinouchis recent remark that they are useless 
in politics 
</TEXT>
