the government monday lifted 
3weekold censorship restrictions on reporting ethnic violence but 
told journalists to censor themselves 
also monday authorities halted a rally by about 600 sinhalese 
buddhist monks who were demanding the expulsion of indian 
peacekeeping troops no violence was reported 
the monks organization which claims to represent 25000 
members said it is prepared to join an armed struggle to oust the 
indian forces monk are an important political force in sri lanka 
the governments announcement that censorship was being lifted 
came 26 hours after the slaying of its chief censor themis guruge 
he was shot to death sunday while walking near his home 
government officials speaking on condition of anonymity blamed 
the slaying of guruge who also headed staterun radio on 
sinhalese extremists foreign minister ranjan wijeratne informed 
local newspaper editors that censorship had been lifted but he 
also warned them be more responsible and maintain 
selfcensorship especially on subversive activities and the indian 
issue 
the censorship had taken heavy criticism from both government 
and opposition lawmakers 
the july 6 announcement of censorship on domestic and foreign 
press coincided with worsening ethnic violence and a deepening 
dispute with india sri lanka has demanded that india pull out 
40000 soldiers deployed as a peacekeeping force 
president ranasinghe premadasa has denounced the indian military 
presence in his nation as a threat to sri lankas sovereignty and 
demanded a pullout by the end of july 
indian peacekeepers arrived in sri lanka two years ago at the 
invitation of premadasas predecessor president junius r 
jayewardene 
india has long said it does not intend to keep its force here 
indefinitely but prime minister rajiv gandhi has said a premature 
withdrawal would lead to even more bloodshed 
more than 15000 people have been killed in ethnic violence that 
started with a separatist revolt by ethnic tamil guerrillas in 1983 
