<TEXT>
the justice department said monday it 
supported a tenfold increase in the maximum fine for criminal 
antitrust violations by corporations to 10 million 
the department noting it is conducting more than 150 grand jury 
investigations of alleged criminal antitrust violations said an 
increase was needed to deter price fixing bid rigging and unlawful 
attempts by corporations to control the market on certain products 
attorney general dick thornburgh said in a statement that he 
supported legislation pending in congress that would increase the 
maximum fine from 1 million to 10 million for corporate antitrust 
violations 
this increase in penalties will send a strong signal to those 
who intend to defraud american consumers or the federal government 
through criminal antitrust conspiracies that the justice department 
takes their criminal conduct most seriously and will see that they 
are appropriately punished thornburgh said 
he issued the statement on the eve of a senate judiciary 
committee hearing on antitrust issues 
the proposal to increase the maximum corporate fine was 
contained in legislation sponsored by sens howard metzenbaum 
dohio and strom thurmond rsc 
james f rill the new assistant attorney general in charge of 
the justice departmentsantitrust division is scheduled to testify 
at tuesdays hearing 
rill noted in a statement that it has been 15 years since 
criminal fines for coprorate antitrust offenders were raised and a 
sizeable increase in fines now is a good way to underscore that 
this criminal activity will not be tolerated 
the fines apply to criminal antitrust violations such as price 
fixing and bid rigging which rill noted is undertaken purely to 
defraud its victims and has no possible economic justification 
rill noting that the antitrust division is conducting more than 
150 grand jury investigations of suspected criminal violations 
said current fines do not appear to be adequately deterring this 
unlawful conduct 
