<TEXT>
despite losing nine military aircraft and six 
crew members to bird collisions over a fiveyear period the 
pentagon still fails to test its planes to see whether they can 
withstand such impacts congressional investigators said monday 
the general accounting office an investigating agency for 
congress reported that from 1983 through 1987 more than 16000 
collisions occurred while most caused only minor damage nine 
planes including a 250 million b1b bomber crashed after 
colliding with birds losses for the period totaled 318 million 
if our military aircraft are not ready for birds how can they 
be ready for combat asked rep john conyers dmich who 
requested the study for the house government operations committee 
which he heads 
the gao did not ask us for a comment and we havent even seen 
it said jan bodanyi a pentagon spokeswoman when asked for 
reaction to the report 
the reports release coincided with opening of house and senate 
consideration of the future of the newgeneration b2 stealth 
bomber at 530 million each the most expensive airplane ever built 
with more expensive aircraft coming into use such as the b1b 
and b2 the value of these losses could become more significant 
the gao said 
the investigators found that specifications are inconsistent for 
the ability of airplanes and engines to withstand bird collisions 
where there are specifications for engines the testing does not 
accurately reflect the sizes and numbers of birds normally sucked 
into jet engines gao said 
the military agency has no testing program to see how well 
airframes the planes body and wings particularly leading edges 
stand up to bird collisions investigators said 
the report suggested requiring in government contracts that 
adequate testing be done and having the pentagon enforce that 
requirement as a way to reduce unnecessary costs 
</TEXT>
