<TEXT>
an international peace and disarmament 
conference began on a discordant note monday when two chinese 
delegates walked out after soviet physicist andrei sakharov called 
for condemnation of chinas crackdown on student protesters 
we cannot forgive or disregard the conduct of the chinese 
government and we must find ways to demonstrate this attitude 
the 1975 nobel peace prize winner said at the opening session of 
the 39th pugwash conference on science and world affairs 
the chinese delegates waited outside the conference room during 
sakharovs 45minute speech which was largely devoted to soviet 
economic and environmental problems then one of them professor 
shi zhongben of beijing university confronted the 68yearold 
human rights activist 
trembling with emotion shi said sakharov did not understand 
chinese affairs and had chosen an inappropriate forum for his 
criticism sakharov remained impassive 
maybe i dont understand all the complexities of the situation 
in china but i think i was right he said later 
we can build peace through international cooperation not by 
interfering in the internal affairs of other countries said shi 
about 200 scientists and statesmen from more than 30 countries 
are attending the fiveday conference being held in the united 
states for the first time in 19 years 
the pugwash conferences grew out of a 1955 statement by bertrand 
russell and albert einstein calling on scientists of all political 
persuasions to devise ways to avoid nuclear war the first 
conference was held in 1957 at pugwash nova scotia 
most of the sessions are devoted to technical arms control 
issues and are closed to the public sakharov spoke during the 
plenary session which was also addressed by gov michael s 
dukakis and sen john kerry dmass 
sakharov who helped develop the soviet hydrogen bomb in the 
1950s later spoke out against soviet human rights abuses and the 
war in afghanistan he was banished to internal exile in the 
industrial city of gorky from 1979 to 1986 when he was personally 
called back to moscow by soviet leader mikhail gorbachev only in 
the past year has he been allowed to travel to the west 
after the chinese army crushed the prodemocracy protest in 
beijings tianenmen square on june 34 with estimates of deaths 
running as high as 3000 the new soviet congress issued a guarded 
statement calling it an internal matter 
but sakharov who is a member of the congress told the pugwash 
delegates we cannot pretend that nothing took place the world 
cannot deal with this chinese government the way it has in the 
past 
speaking through a translator sakharov compared the violence in 
china to the soviet armys use of poison gas and sharpened shovels 
to disperse a nationalist demonstration in soviet georgia in april 
killing at least 20 people he said both events showed the dangers 
faced by democracy movements around the world 
shi the senior chinese delegate stood up about halfway through 
the speech as soon as sakharov made the remarks about china he 
was quickly followed by the second delegate niu qiang of the 
chinese peoples association for peace and disarmament 
two other chinese delegates kept their seats in another part of 
the room but it was unclear whether they did so deliberately or 
failed to notice the departure of shi and niu 
despite the incident shi and niu said they planned to attend 
the rest of the conference which will explore ways to convert 
warmer eastwest relations into practical agreements on arms 
control and verification 
m innas ali a nuclear physicist from bangladesh said 
sakharovs confrontation with the chinese did not dampen the 
optimism of most delegates who believe the time is ripe for arms 
accords 
dukakis and kerry urged the delegates to take advantage of the 
sovietamerican rapprochement 
it may be a onceinalifetime opportunity said dukakis 
the unsuccessful democratic candidate for president 
