<TEXT>
federal spending on major commodity programs 
is down from what administration budget analysts forecast in 
january an agriculture department analysis showed monday 
total outlays in the fiscal year that began oct 1 are now 
projected at less than 135 billion about 360 million below the 
january prediction 
programs include payments to farmers for participating in annual 
crop programs in the case of major crops such as wheat corn and 
cotton the programs provide price supports and other benefits in 
return for taking land out of production 
but some other commodities also are covered including price 
support operations for soybeans peanuts tobacco honey sugar 
dairy products and wool 
outlays for corn and other feed grains in 1989 were indicated in 
january at about 304 billion the new midsession review 
raised the estimate to 417 billion at the same time spending 
for wheat rice and upland cotton programs was reduced by more than 
13 billion from the january forecast 
allowing for adjustments in other programs administered by the 
departments commodity credit corp total spending for the various 
agricultural commodities was reduced a net of 86 million to less 
than 703 billion for this fiscal year 
other ccc spending including 375 billion for aid to farmers 
who suffered severe losses from the 1988 drought put the fiscal 
1989 total at just under 135 billion compared with the january 
estimate of more than 138 billion 
looking at 1990 the report said total ccc spending could drop 
to just over 113 billion down 231 million from what was 
projected in january 
scott steele an agriculture department budget analyst said the 
boost in feedgrain outlays from the level initially projected was 
a result of new quarterly grain inventory figures in january those 
showed more feed grain on hand than had been indicated previously 
it was this larger inventory that we did not take into account 
when we did the budget that was published by the outgoing reagan 
administration jan 9 and later adopted by president bush he said 
steele said in an interview that the jan 9 projections were 
based on supplyand demand readings last november the new review 
took into consideration the grain figures that were issued jan 13 
looking at fiscal 1990 which will begin oct 1 the new report 
showed total ccc outlays at less than 114 billion down about 
231 million from what had been projected in january 
spending on feed grains in 198990 was indicated at nearly 707 
billion up from the 556 billion projected in january declines 
from the january projections were shown for wheat rice and cotton 
