safety board investigators has interviewed 26 of united airlines 
flight 232s passengers so far ntsb spokesman ted lopatkiewicz 
said monday 
most were among those still hospitalized after wednesdays crash 
landing in sioux city that killed 111 people lopatkiewicz said 
questionnaires will be sent to all adults among the 185 
survivors the investigation spokesman said in a telephone 
interview from sioux city 
lopatkiewicz said the team will document the survivability of 
the accident and try to find out what precautions were most 
effective in preventing injury and death when the jetliner burst 
into flames flipped over landed on its back and split apart in a 
cornfield near the sioux city airport 
the team will try to interview all adults traveling with 
children to see what happened to the youngsters after the pilot 
told passengers to prepare for a crash landing 
among concerns to be addressed he said is the fact that 
several infants were traveling free in their parents arms without 
assigned seats a common practice on domestic flights 
