<TEXT>
a 60 million federal attempt to detail 
environmental problems at nuclear weapons plants may not be 
reliable because energy department staff members didnt keep good 
notes the departments inspector general reported monday 
the department said it disagreed with the igs assessment 
aides who conducted the threeyear survey of environmental 
problems at the plants produced poorly organized supporting 
documents said the report by inspector general john c layton 
the supporting documents were mainly log books with notes taken 
in the field they generally were not recorded in complete 
sentences and were not detailed enough to function as a memory aid 
even to team members who may be involved in hundreds of findings 
at dozens of locations the report said 
the notes were neither indexed nor organized in a way that 
would allow anyone to trace facts or conclusions in the reports 
back to the source team members acknowledged that it would be 
difficult and time consuming to locate information in the backup 
documents 
the 60 million inventory was ordered under secretary john 
herrington in the reagan administration it was not immediately 
clear whether it will be used to set cleanup priorities for the 
highly contaminated nuclear weapons plants 
layton said the shortcomings in the way the plants were 
evaluated undermine the credibility of the process and call into 
question the usefulness of the surveys 
decisionmakers cannot be assured that the 60 million effort 
provides a sound basis for prioritizing environmental problems 
layton said in a memo to energy secretary james watkins 
the energy departments response included in the report said 
the poorly organized records criticized by the inspector general 
werent intended to be reference materials 
the preliminary reports produced by the field staff were sent to 
the various plants where they were not found to be deficient 
the department said 
layton said theres a chance some contamination may not be 
adequately indentified and theres a chance critical projects may 
lose limited cleanup money because they werent put in the right 
place on the priority list 
but the department said the inspector general extrapolated 
beyond what is reasonable 
layton briefly mentioned his findings during a congressional 
hearing last week but details were not available until the report 
came off the press 
