<TEXT>
lawmakers unveiled draft legislation monday to 
impose a ceasefire in the battle over logging in the ancient 
forests of the pacific northwest but objections from a vermont 
senator sidetracked plans for immediate subcommittee action on the 
bill 
sens mark hatfield rore and brock adams dwash planned 
to ask the full senate appropriations committee to approve the 
legislation tuesday despite concerns from sen patrick leahy dvt 
leahy both at the beginning of the interior appropriations 
subcommittee meeting and in a letter to full committee chairman 
robert byrd dwv said he was deeply disturbed that 
provisions in the bill might preempt the right of environmentalists 
to appeal timber sales to the courts 
leahys skepticism dampened the excitement of the bills 
sponsors who hope to ensure an adequate supply of logs to keep the 
regions mills operating over the next 14 months as well as 
protect some of the oldgrowth forests that are prime habitat for 
the northern spotted owl 
the bill calls for the sale of 10 billion board feet of timber 
off of the national forests and bureau of land management lands in 
oregon and washington over the next 14 months 
hatfield said that is about 10 percent less than the amount of 
timber that would be sold if some sales werent blocked by lawsuits 
to protect the spotted owl 
in addition the plan discourages logging significantly large 
blocks of oldgrowth forests a policy known as minimum 
fragmentation 
under the proposal significant stands of oldgrowth would have 
at least eight trees per acre that are at least 300 years old or 
are 40 inches in diameter environmentalists would be allowed to 
release 125 billion board feet of the almost 2 billion board feet 
of timber sales currently enjoined by federal courts in portland 
and seattle 
i am concerned that an appeal and judicial exemption process 
that started with isolated sales could expand to a region and may 
soon become national in scope said leahy who also is chairman 
of the senate agriculture committee which has jurisdiction over 
the us forest service 
leahy who has close ties to environmental groups said he was 
well aware that forest products were essential to the economic 
health of the region but added the right of appeal was also of 
vital importance 
hatfield agreed to postpone consideration of the bill until the 
full committee meeting 
the sales have been temporarily enjoined by pending lawsuits 
that claim overlogging in oldgrowth forests is threatening the 
northern spotted owl with extinction the owl hunts and nests 
almost exclusively in ancient forests 
the agreement would prohibit environmentalists from using 
injunctions to block timber sales in the next fiscal year which 
starts oct 1 
