35yearold case 
in 1987 us district judge richard rogers of topeka ruled that 
topekas public school district no longer had any illegal or 
intentional separation of races 
in june the appeals court overturned rogers ruling saying the 
topeka school system had not done enough to overcome remnants of 
the segregated school system that existed before the us supreme 
court decided the landmark brown vs topeka board of education case 
in 1954 the appeals court ordered rogers to devise a remedy for 
what it called the racially identifiable schools in topeka 
topeka superintendent gary livingston said he and his staff are 
still unsure what the appeals court action means and he will be 
meeting with attorneys 
the 1954 supreme court decision held that the separate but 
equal concept for public schools was unconstitutional 
the case was reopened in 1979 when the parents of 17 topeka 
public schoolchildren sought a decision on whether the schools had 
eliminated traces of the segregated system the parents included 
linda brown buckner who as a student in 1954 gave the case its 
name 
