<TEXT>
 
editors note in vast alaska highways are scarce villages 
remote and cars have limited use get a horse no get an airplane 
heres one mans crusade to honor the aviation pioneers in 
americas flyingest state 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the remains of the airplane lay 
rotting in the slimy thicket of a gulch wings clipped tail shorn 
body stove in a sorry looking carcass guarded by squadrons of 
bloodthirsty mosquitoes 
to ted spencer it shone like a jewel 
it can be restored spencer was saying stalking the 
remains nodding yes it can his boots made sucking sounds as 
he bounded around in the muck snapping pictures oblivious to the 
mosquitoes his glee obvious 
i heard about this airplane last year and didnt believe it 
was true when i came and saw it for myself saw ptarmigan ii 
painted on its nose my heart leapt look you can still read it 
ted spencer is the director of the alaska aviation heritage 
museum which occupies a corner of the anchorage airport 
at 42 he couples a childlike exuberance for airplanes with a 
professorial knowledge of them especially airplanes of the 
ptarmigan ii vintage 
his aim is to document through records and artifacts one of 
the most colorful periods in american history the 20 years before 
world war ii when the aviation as it was called came to 
alaska 
the old airplanes themselves of course are the prime 
artifacts a proud array of them restored to look like new 
contrast handsomely with their modern counterparts flying overhead 
what those aviation pioneers did in alaska was no less 
extraordinary says spencer than men landing on the moon what 
they accomplished had immediate effects and they were more 
significant in alaska than the advent of aviation in any other 
state they liberated americas last frontier 
flying out to willow creek recently there being no other way 
to cover the 275 miles from anchorage spencer pointed out the 
window to a beach on the kuskokwim river near the village of 
mcgrath as if to document his own claim he scribbled a note to 
his fellow passenger 
carl ben eielson flew first airmail to that spot feb 1924 
singleengine dehavilland dh4 open cockpit came from fairbanks 
threehour flight in winter 
before eielsons flight it took 20 days to make that 300mile 
mail run by dog team you can see a photograph of eielson and his 
airplane at the heritage museum 
more out of continuing necessity than nostalgia for those glory 
days of epic feats alaska has remained by far the flyingest state 
in the nation 
according to federal aviation administration figures alaska 
per capita has eight times as many pilots and 15 times as many 
planes as the us average it works out to one pilot for every 55 
alaskans and one plane for every 57 alaskas 9682 licensed pilots 
average 132 flying hours a year compared with a national average 
including alaska of 49 hours 
hood lake in anchorage is the worlds largest seaplane base 
merrill field which handles only general aviation light planes 
for personal and charter use is busier than the international 
airports in seattletacoma salt lake city and orlando fla 
its hard for people who havent experienced alaska to 
visualize its vastness and its terrain said the faas paul 
steuke 
we have only about 533000 people most of them scattered in 
settlements that would be utterly isolated without the airplane 
our few roads very few are like streams without tributaries you 
cant get to them even if you could theyre often impassable in 
winter 
add to that four huge mountain ranges and unpredictable 
weather systems boiling out of the pacific even skilled pilots 
have to stay on their toes in alaska 
how much more so says spencer for the aviation pioneers who 
established that almost mythic breed known as bush pilots during 
the 1920s and 1930s they became the most popular and honored men in 
alaska 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0205 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
imagine flying out over uncharted territory through narrow 
mountain passes in open cockpits with no maps no weather reports 
no radios no landing strips no places to refuel 
eskimos saw airplanes long before they saw automobiles and came 
to regard the pilots as paracletes they brought medicine to the 
villages fresh fruit locations of caribou herds news of 
relatives in other settlements 
they took trappers into the bush and came back on appointed days 
to fetch them they hauled miners and supplies to gold camps 
hauled the sick to hospitals 
a pilot named leo moore hauled a cow from anchorage so an ailing 
baby in mcgrath could have fresh milk a pilot named sig wien 
hauled a chessboard on his 90mile trips between point lay and 
wainwright so two distant friends could have a game 
by 1939 alaskas small airplanes and hearty pilots were hauling 
23 times as many passengers per capita as the airlines of the 
united states and 1000 times as much freight 
empty wooden boxes labeled stanavo gas each of which held two 
fivegallon cans of airplane fuel littered the countryside 
stacked in outposts and trappers cabins they came to be known as 
alaska cupboards 
on a stopover at flat on the way to willow creek spencer found 
a stanavo box in good shape and brought it back with him 
if i dont find things like this myself they might not be 
found he said we dont have much help and the museum is 
practically broke were in a constant financial crisis 
john miscovich who is 71 was born in a mining camp at flat 
about eight miles from willow creek and remembers when the 
aviation reached there it opened up a whole new era 
he also remembers when wiley post crashlanded there in 1933 
safely but it was a close call spencer videotaped miscovichs 
recollection of the episode 
it was miscovich who told ted spencer about the abandoned 
remains of the plane at willow creek how the pilot had salvaged 
the planes engines after a crash and left the rest the boxy 
fuselage miscovich said had for a time served as a makeshift 
toolshed before it finally wound up in the gulch 
spencer has in his museum files the history of very nearly every 
bush plane the pioneer airmen flew 
i knew the ptarmigan ii was a ford trimotor probably the 
first in alaska in fact i had a picture of it and of its pilot 
frank dorbandt 
dorbandt bought it from an air service in the states which had 
named it west wind ii it was built in 1928 dorbandt bought it in 
1934 brought it to alaska and renamed it ptarmigan ii there never 
was a ptarmigan i 
dorbandt was one of the really early pilots he participated 
in the search for eielson 
eielson at age 32 had crashed in a storm over siberia his 
fellow bush pilots mounted a search and one of them joe crosson 
found the wreckage and eielsons body weeks later soviet airmen 
had also joined in the search and a soviet ship returned the body 
to alaska wrapped in an american flag sewn from red and blue 
muslin and white ship canvas 
beginning with eielsons crash in 1930 fully twothirds of the 
planes in alaska were wrecked beyond repair over the next 10 years 
less serious crackups were commonplace in fact pilots came to 
expect some minor damage on every landing 
but they persevered spencer says as a result we now have 
a fairly intricate network of air travel that unifies the whole 
state 
spencer has arranged with the national guard to fly out in a 
helicopter the first week in september and lift the remains of 
ptarmigan ii from the gulch at willow creek 
it will join its brothers in that panoply of history each in 
flying condition each with its own contribution to a storied era 
that opened up a hostile land 
ptarmigan ii will have a place of honor spencer says it 
will fly again 
</TEXT>
