<TEXT>
phillip lopate prefers sitting behind a 
typewriter to standing atop a soapbox he distrusts movements 
getting caught up in any event larger than himself 
a man of caution he remembers with discomfort the 1960s group 
ritual of passing a body from one set of arms to another what he 
does trust is the individual voice expressed in writing through 
the personal essay 
i think its important because its a direct conversation 
between the writer and the reader and has the flavor of 
personality said lopate author of against joie de vivre 
poseidon press 1895 a collection of personal essays 
if you believe in individuals and individual voices then its 
one of the ways of getting a sense of dialogue going a personal 
essay gives you a model of a human being in all his hesitations and 
faults and confusions 
his tales are more of observation than experience lopate 
examines the myth of samson and delilah deconstructs the manners 
of dinner parties and in the title essay attacks mindless 
optimism 
i think i have a streak of detachmant which is very suitable 
for being a writer and maybe not so suitable for other activities 
its very hard to knock me off course im always watching in some 
way some part of me refuses to be swept away he said in an 
interview 
when i write im able to get a sense of perspective so that 
experiences which are too painful for someone else to contemplate 
i can think about with a certain humor a certain wryness and begin 
to shape them 
he is admittedly a believer in committing experiences to 
memory as they occur even at the risk of reducing their emotional 
impact detachment is vital he insists a way of examining an 
issue to its fullest and working through to a wellconsidered 
conclusion 
i tend to analyze and brood over what has happened to me until 
i make little stories lopate said 
my essays have a strong storytelling impulse sometimes 
theyre really on the borderline between fiction and nonfiction 
theyre shaped in the narrative way theyre about characters 
people as characters 
lopate who worked as a writerinresidence at a public school 
in manhattan uses this approach in suicide of a schoolteacher 
examining the feelings brought on when a colleague takes his own 
life 
when i write about something traumatic im trying to overcome 
the pain and put it behind me he said then i think i dont 
have to write about it anymore ive dealt with it but i also 
write to hold onto things that would otherwise be lost its a 
salvaging process 
lopate attended columbia university in the early 60s acquiring 
a passion for films that never subsided he is currently on the 
selection committee of the new york film festival and credits 
movies with helping develop his skills at narration 
sometimes you learn an art by studying another art i learned 
the grammar of film and it helped me to write theres a great deal 
of cinematic influence in my writing a lot of times the scene 
will unroll as im experiencing it 
in chekhov for children lopate describes the sometimes 
tortuous process of directing a dozen adolescents in the russian 
playwrights bleak uncle vanya 
he knows that detachment doesnt work with children or the 
theater and writes of the emotional highs and lows experienced 
during rehearsals 
children are always surprising he said i watch them and 
find them very dramatic they dont tone down their response so 
much theyll tell you they hate you or love you they dont 
disguise very much 
that can be invigorating and it can also be humiliating if a 
kid doesnt like you its more of a setback than if an adult 
doesnt like you because you feel theyre responding very 
naturally 
against joie de vivre is lopates seventh book he has also 
published a previous collection of essays and an account of his 
public school experience being with children two volumes of 
poetry and two novels including the wellreceived the rug 
merchant in 1987 
lopate views the world as a stage and himself a dispassionate 
critic interpreting the actors performances to the audience at 
large 
some writers are fascinated with language i want to write 
beautifully and eloquently but much more important is for me to 
capture character on the page starting with my own character and 
using that to spread outward to use myself as a messenger that 
will bring back the world 
he sees himself as fighting to maintain integrity in a world 
where people hide their real feelings for lopate the personal 
essay is a written form of protest a modern equivalent of burning 
his draft card 
theres something almost subversive about the personal 
essay he said it empowers the individual i also think that 
in a time when many writers are afraid to say explicitly what they 
think as in fiction when they show but they dont tell too much 
the essay becomes a place where the writer testifies without a 
disguise of what she or he knows 
</TEXT>
