<TEXT>
a littlenoticed supreme court ruling making 
it easier for employers to limit older workers fringe benefits has 
spurred members of congress to seek agediscrimination barriers 
many thought had been in place for decades 
lawmakers and advocates for the elderly are pushing legislation 
to nullify the june 23 ruling that bias in benefits such as health 
and retirement plans is not automatically banned under the 1967 age 
discrimination in employment act 
in the wake of the ruling employers are probably going to 
start tightening up on what fringes they offer to older workers 
said vicki gottlich an attorney with the national senior citizens 
law center employers may start rethinking how theyre going to 
provide benefits 
however doug mcdowell whose washington law firm mcguiness and 
williams represents management in employment cases said companies 
arent likely to make major cutbacks that would hurt worker morale 
theres a labor shortage in a lot of areas instead of laying 
off people they want to keep them im not sure people would want 
to stay with an employer who said everyone over age 65 is going to 
lose benefits mcdowell said 
the government has long interpreted the age discrimination act 
as letting employers limit fringes for older workers only if it 
would cost more to offer them the same benefits given younger 
employees for example life insurance 
but the supreme court in an ohio case said the law bans biased 
benefit plans only in cases where the disparities are part of an 
intent to discriminate in some nonfringebenefit aspect of 
employment such as hiring or firing 
justice thurgood marshall in a strong dissent from the 72 
majority decision said the ruling immunizes virtually all 
employee benefit programs from liability under the age 
discrimination act 
it is difficult to believe that congress intended to 
immunize acts of unabashed discrimination against older workers 
marshall wrote 
horace deets executive director of the american association of 
retired persons said that while the ruling got little attention 
amid the excitement over longawaited court decisions on abortion 
and flagburning it was an absolute shocker to the aging 
community 
for years the assumption has been that benefits are covered 
under the age discrminiation act as would be hiring and firing 
deets said this puts older workers at a distinct disadvantage 
the decision came in a lawsuit filed by june betts who began 
working in 1978 as a speech pathologist at the hamilton county 
board of mental retardation and developmental disabilites when her 
work deteriorated due to alzheimers disease the 61yearold ms 
betts in 1985 was given the choice of unpaid medical leave or 
retiring with a standard pension of 15850 a month 
because she was over 60 she was denied a third option of 
disability retirement with benefits of 355 a month 
lower courts upheld ms betts contention that it was a 
violation of the act to deny disability benefits solely because of 
her age but the supreme court said congress had left the 
employee benefit battle for another day when it enacted the 
antidiscrimination law in 1967 
the equal employment opportunity commission which enforces the 
age discrimination act filed a brief supporting ms betts and 
stating its belief that the law required some sort of cost 
justification in order to permit an employer to avoid a charge of 
discrimination 
the courts ruling to the contrary is under review and its 
impact on cases pending has not been determined said eeoc 
spokeswoman margaret fernandez 
the rulings biggest impact will be in disability and severance 
benefits which sometimes are designed to convert to pensions at a 
certain age or after a specified time according to jim klein of 
towers perrin a new york consulting firm that often represents 
employers but most employers already are accustomed to applying 
the act to benefit plans and are unlikely to make big changes 
because of the betts ruling klein said 
any aftereffects of the ruling could well be shortlived given 
widespread interest on capitol hill in obviating it 
sen john heinz of pennsylvania ranking republican on the 
senate special committee on aging has introduced legislation to 
extend age discrimination barriers to fringe benefits and sen 
howard metzenbaum dohio also is considering legislative options 
in the house edward roybal dcalif chairman of the select 
committee on aging said he would introduce legislation we in 
congress cannot allow older workers to go unprotected in such a 
critical part of the employment relationship as employee benefit 
plans 
</TEXT>
