<DOCNO> AP890724-0253 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a refinancing agreement between mexico and its 
creditor banks offers a glimmer of hope to the debtstrapped third 
world but success of the plan hinges on how far the banks are 
willing to go government officials and private bankers said monday 
the administration which provided a final push over the weekend 
to get the agreement hailed the package as a landmark success for 
its debtreduction initiative unveiled by treasury secretary 
nicholas brady on march 10 
however the banks that will implement the plan were more 
reserved in their enthusiasm with many contending that it was too 
soon to say how much debt relief they will provide to mexico 
because they were still examining the fine print of the agreement 
at the moment were exploring our options fraser seitel a 
spokesman for chase manhattan corp said in a typical comment 
were looking at the entire third world debt package 
the bush administration hopes to use the mexican agreement to 
set a precedent that will facilitate debt relief in other 
countries with venezuela and the philippines considered the two 
leading candidates to follow mexicos lead 
the administration has made debt reduction a key component of 
its foreign policy believing that the only way to ensure the 
survival of emerging democracies in latin america is to reverse the 
decadelong slide in living standards caused by the crushing 13 
trillion third world debt burden 
the brady plan for debt relief is seeking to slash this debt by 
establishing incentives to get commerical banks to voluntarily 
forgive a portion of the loans 
however banking analysts said it was unclear whether the 
incentives being offered in the mexican package were sufficient to 
trigger a substantial writedown of the debt 
in the case of mexico the debtreduction package provides the 
commercial banks with three options 
on the debt relief side they can cut 35 percent off the face 
value of the current loans or they can agree to reduce interest 
rates to 625 percent down from about 10 percent currently 
banks also have the option of simply providing new loans 
the administration estimated that the various options could save 
mexico about 15 billion annually off the 5 billion to 55 
billion it must pay to service its 54 billion in commercial bank 
debt 
however the administration stressed that this was a rough 
estimate and would vary depending on individual decisions made by 
the 500 commercial banks located in the united states japan and 
europe that hold the mexican debt 
rep charles schumer dny and a leading congressional expert 
on third world debt said that the mexican agreement appeared 
seriously flawed because it did not provide enough incentives for 
banks to opt for the two debt reduction options rather than simply 
piling on new debt 
a lot of the banks without the necessary carrots or sticks 
are going to stick with the familiar approach of supplying new 
money to pay old debt schumer said 
schumer said that approach has proven to be a disaster over the 
past seven years since 1982 when the debt crisis first erupted 
third world debt has more than doubled from 600 billion to the 
current 13 trillion 
rep john lafalce dny said the mexican agreement did not 
represent any longlasting breakthrough in mexicos debt 
situation he said while the amount of debtreduction was likely 
to be small mexico would benefit in the next couple of years with 
an infusion of new money to get its economy started again 
cynthia latta an economist with drimcgraw hill said that the 
administration apparently failed to get as many concessions as they 
could from the commercial banks because they were so anxious to get 
an agreement 
it looks like they desperately wanted to do a deal and get 
something signed to prove that their debt strategy could work 
she said it is a surface agreement that allows the 
administration to claim a success but it leaves a lot of unanswered 
questions 
the administration had hoped that president bush would be able 
to present a completed mexican package during the sevennation 
economic summit last week in paris 
when that deadline was missed brady stepped up his lobbying 
efforts he brought the bankers and mexican negotiators to 
washington over the weekend for meetings at the treasury which 
were also attended by federal reserve chairman alan greenspan 
after two days of discussions at the us treasury final 
agreement was reached late sunday in time for mexican president 
carlos salinas de gortari to announce the breakthrough during a 
televised broadcast saying the proposal would answer the the cry 
of mexicans to return to growth 
</TEXT>
