<TEXT>
ferruzzi group on monday called for a study of 
chicago board of trade operations in a followup of the soybean 
processors criticism of the exchanges emergency order that 
required traders to reduce their holdings in soybean futures 
contracts 
david h swanson president of central soya co and a member of 
ferruzzis executive committee said the emergency order 
illustrated that the exchange had failed to keep up with the global 
expansion of commodities trading 
he said a study of the cbot should look at its grain delivery 
system regulations market stability committee structure and 
market trends swanson said such a study should be undertaken by a 
group made up of soybean farmers processors and others with a 
stake in the soybean market 
the agricultural market is becoming truly global in nature 
more than ever it requires a strong and predictable chicago board 
of trade swanson said at a news conference 
as it stands now it is open to question whether the market is 
serving that function 
the board of trade on july 11 ordered ferruzzi group part of 
the italian grain conglomerate ferruzzi fianziaria spa and other 
major traders to liquidate contracts for july delivery or sale of 
millions of bushels of soybeans 
that decision touched off wild swings in soybean prices and the 
exchanges action has been widely questioned by farm groups 
cbot officials said the exchange was worried that soybean 
supplies were insufficient for meeting large holdings of contracts 
for july delivery of soybeans in the final days of trading in that 
contract 
swanson said monday that ferruzzi was holding contracts for 
delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans in july he said those 
holdings were built up because of concerns ferruzzi might not be 
able to fill export orders because of the reduction in soybean 
supplies due to the 1988 drought 
it is both incredible and unacceptable that a market with 
international authority and indeed global responsibility can be 
in a crisis over 20 million bushels of beans he said 
the chicago board of trade refused to comment on ferruzzis call 
for the study however a cbot spokesman who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said the exchange conducts internal reviews on a regular 
basis 
we have an entire department the department of economic 
analysis and planning that reviews the market on a regular 
basis said the spokesman it adjusts contracts if they need 
adjusting 
swanson said that despite the global nature of the soybean 
market the number of participants had declined 
with fewer but larger players hedging needs of the major 
firms have increased dramatically he said do the cbots 
operating practices accommodate this changed market 
swanson also said a study should look into whether options have 
reduced futures trading and increased price volatility 
futures are contracts for the delivery of a specified amount of 
a commodity such as soybeans at a future time for a specific 
price options give a speculator the option to buy or sell futures 
contracts at a specific price during a certain period of time 
options are the preferred instrument of many farmers the 
cbot spokesman said when they enter to an options agreement it 
puts a floor on the price but they are free to take a better price 
should it occur 
