goldome bank the thrift institution in the 
midst of a major restructuring under new leadership on monday 
reported a record 225 million secondquarter loss 
goldome said changes in its investment portfolio the sale of 
several business units writedowns on nonperforming assets and 
layoffs accounted for more than twothirds of the loss the rest 
came from continuing operations 
thomas cooper goldome president and chief operating officer 
said some losses are losses and some are investments these 
losses will actually save the company in coming quarters 
it was the seventh consecutive quarterly loss for the company 
one of the nations largest savings and loan institutions goldome 
lost 195 million in the second quarter a year ago 
for the second quarter this year net interest income was 22 
million compared to 507 million a year ago primarily as a 
result of higher interest rates the bank said operating expenses 
were 178 million compared to 102 million last year 
cooper a former president of bank of america said in april 
when he took over as head of goldome that he intended to turn the 
bank into a customerdriven organization 
goldome immediately began selling off divisions not related to 
the companys traditional mortgage markets and announced a plan to 
trim employment by 20 percent 
as part of the restructuring goldome reported the sale of 14 
billion of highrisk and junk bond investments at a cost of more 
than 55 million the reduction of 48 million in real estate and 
nonaccrual loans and layoffs and a hiring freeze that trimmed 
payroll costs by 19 million 
cooper said the moves will serve as a platform for our return 
to profitability 
goldome with 14 billion in assets operates in two dozen 
states 
