<DOCNO> AP890724-0274 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
paramount communications inc abandoned 
its 122 billion hostile bid for time inc on monday after the 
delaware supreme court upheld a lower court decision allowing time 
to proceed with its 14 billion buyout of warner communications inc 
we find no error of law by the court of chancery justice 
henry r horsey announced as the threejudge panel unanimously 
sustained a ruling by judge william t allen thereby affirming the 
rights of corporate directors to decide the future course of their 
companies 
the decision ended paramounts sevenweek bid to acquire time 
paramount issued a statement that it was dropping its 200 a share 
buyout offer but would continue trying to expand through 
acquisitions mergers joint ventures or partnerships 
we believe in making bold moves when they are in the best 
interest of paramount communications shareholders said paramount 
chairman martin davis we have just demonstrated that in our 
offer for time 
paramount and several of times biggest shareholders 
unsuccessfully had sought an injunction against times tender offer 
for warner claiming that time should be forced to consider 
paramounts buyout offer 
the tender offer for warner expired at 5 pm edt and time 
announced it held more than 117 million warner shares or about 58 
percent of the companys outstanding common stock time said it 
would announce tuesday the exact number of shares tendered under 
its offer 
under its 70 a share offer time was to purchase slightly more 
than half of warners common stock and exchange a combination of 
cash and securities valued at 70 a share for the rest time said 
shareholders would start to be paid for the tendered shares on 
monday 
when their merger is complete a process expected to take 
several months the new time warner inc will be the worlds 
largest communications concern 
paramount said it would not pursue a bid for time warner 
allens ruling gave corporate directors latitude in defending 
against unwanted takeover bids that they claim interfere with a 
companys longterm strategy 
the judge said the proposed timewarner deal which was 
announced in march three months before paramount launched its bid 
was the result of longterm business planning and that paramount 
and times shareholders could not interfere 
paramount has contended that once time announced its plan to 
merge with warner it effectively placed itself up for sale and 
under delaware law therefore had to consider paramounts offer 
during more than two hours of arguments before the supreme court 
monday paramount attorney melvyn cantor said times board had a 
fiduciary duty to inquire into paramounts initial 175 a share 
buyout offer 
we dont question that timewarner is a good deal cantor 
said but he contended time shareholders should have had a chance 
to vote on whether paramounts acquisition of the company would 
have been a better deal in the short term 
michael klein an attorney for major time shareholders 
including texas investor robert m bass said thousands of the 
companys stockholders opposed the timewarner merger he argued 
that based on previous delaware court rulings the board was 
obligated to consider paramounts offer 
but justice andrew gt moore interjected that kleins argument 
would make a board hostage to anyone who walked in with a bid 
regardless of a companys longrange plans 
klein said after the court ruled that the decision tilted 
delaware law in favor of management he predicted attorneys would 
advise corporations to develop an appearance of a longterm 
plan to ward off potential takeover bids 
when time attorney robert joffe presented his case monday the 
justices asked why times tender offer for warner which replaced 
an earlier stockswap merger plan was not submitted to a vote by 
time shareholders at the companys annual meeting in june 
joffe said a vote was not required because the deal did not 
involve the issuing of new time stock furthermore he said after 
paramount announced its bid on june 6 the market for time stock 
was in disarray and the price of the shares was seesawing 
this was hardly the situation to have an unimpassioned 
evaluation of future value and get a fair vote he said 
joffe contended times plans to merge with warner would give 
shareholders greater value in the long term than paramounts 200 a 
share offer 
the case was heard in delaware because all three companies 
like many of the biggest us corporations are incorporated 
there because so many major corporations subject to delaware laws 
the time case likely will have implications for other companies in 
the future 
the supreme court planned to issue a written decision at some 
point in the future 
the justices ruling was widely expected even before the hearing 
began as arguments proceeded and were televised live by cable 
news network times stock dropped on the new york stock exchange 
time stock closed down 1 at 13750 a share warner stock 
rose162 to 6612 a share and paramount rose 187 to 5937 
a share 
time stock which traded at 126 a share before the paramount 
bid rose to a high of 18275 before falling back in recent weeks 
as investors became increasingly pessimistic about the chances for 
paramounts success 
</TEXT>
